<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM PROTESTERS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb  9  2:11:33 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
  When I left Vietnam in August of 1967, the casualties were far less than the 58,000 names that are presently on &quot;the Wall&quot;.  Thanks to the likes of Jane Fonda and Bill Clinton, who according to NVA Commander Giap, encouraged them (NVA)to persist for one more day, week, month, eventually the protesters in America will help to acheive their goal.<br>
  One only needs to watch as the movies of the invasion of the South clearly show the masses of the South Vietnamese people in flight towards further South, ahead of the NVA advance.<br>
  Who would imagine,  there would one day be a memorial wall bearing a list of names of those who paid the unltimate sacrifice ?  <br>
  Were it not for the war protesters, the list of names and the size of the wall would today be much smaller. As Giap reported in his book, the Tet '68 offensive was considered by his staff as a failure, they were on their knees and on the verge of surrender, due to their supply lines being intercepted, and their troops were without supplies after many combat battle losses and failures.  Then they received reports of Walter Cronkite reporting the US Embassy was overun.  A false report, as they'd only entered the grounds and had not caprtured the building as Cronkite reported.<br>
  Fortunately,  in WWII there was no movie actress kissing and hugging the Nazi's and spitting on American POW's. The White House did not prevent the shelling of the beaches prior to the D-Day invasion, and did not limit the bombing of the Schwienfurt ball bearing factories. Had this happened then, the results of WWII may well have been different.
